The Comprehensive Crisis in Lebanon
Beirut —— Looking back, it usually seems that there are signs before financial crises occur; however, they rarely clearly indicate the direction of history.
Lebanon's current situation is the same — a foreseeable crisis has plunged the country into a state of high instability.
Since the end of Lebanon's long-term civil war (1975-1990), its economic and political systems have been supported by external borrowing, which inevitably led to a continuous rise in public debt.
At some point, the inflow of foreign capital had to stop. This point arrived at the end of 2019, followed by a series of negative shocks.
The sudden stop of this capital has brought about a serious triple crisis to this country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit is as high as 25% of its gross domestic product, and its exports are too small to even cover the costs of necessary imports.
The second issue is fiscal.
Lebanon's public debt now totals more than 150% of its gross domestic product.
Government revenue is collapsing under the pressure of economic recession, and the budget deficit is already huge, accounting for 10% of GDP in 2019, and is still rapidly expanding.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Main banks, as the main recipients of foreign capital inflows, have made substantial investments in Lebanese sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their investment portfolios), and are now basically insolvent.
These crises together have pushed Lebanon's economy into a deep abyss.
Companies eager for loans and imports have begun laying off workers or shutting down completely.
An economic recession could lead to a depression in Lebanon.
The main source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political economy is not oil, but remittances, which attract investments due to high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate tied to the dollar.
So it is in no way surprising that there are signs of "Dutch disease" everywhere: deposits have grown to more than 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has reduced the national savings rate to an implausible level — 3% of GDP.
Inequality is high and is still rising.
Between 2000 and 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50%, greatly weakening tradable sectors.
Lebanon has been losing its educated youth due to a lack of export goods and services.
But more importantly, large-scale capital inflows have allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than performance.
These elites have siphoned wealth from both the public and private sectors to establish a bloated patronage network.
While this has ensured political stability in this originally chaotic region, it has failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is discontinuous and unreliable, while broader macroeconomic challenges remain completely unresolved.
The financial crisis triggered a political uprising.
A mass revolutionary movement took to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Nevertheless, so far, the country's regime has overwhelmingly favored the elite in its response to Lebanon's economic issues, indicating that this crisis might eventually be "resolved" with the support of the poor and the middle class, and further consolidate sectarian politics.
For example, the state refused to introduce capital controls, allowing the main shareholders of each bank, including the ruling politicians, to decide how to allocate cash withdrawals.
In practice, this allows the elites to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens struggle to access their deposits.
Moreover, the central bank has cut deposit rates but not the public debt interest rates, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite the continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon continues to repay its external debt, mainly owed to domestic banks.
There are signs that it may begin selling state assets at fire sale prices to elite-linked entities.
Meanwhile, the official exchange rate remains unchanged, while elites are allowed access to dollars at a low exchange rate, whereas ordinary citizens face the reality of the rapidly declining free market exchange rate. The current free market exchange rate is discounted by 40%.
When the country starts printing liras to pay public sector wages, the depreciation will accelerate.
Factually, the central bank has already been paying interest on dollar deposits in liras (dollar deposits account for more than 80% of all deposits), thereby creating conditions to eliminate public debt through inflation.
By shifting the cost of debt reduction through "liraization" via depositor ownership onto depositors, the bank's equity is basically spared.
If this situation becomes a reality, Lebanon's middle class will be significantly reduced due to the decrease in real wages and pensions as well as the liquidation of savings.
The emigration process of educated young people will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the immigrant community — on which this system relies — will be damaged.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poor population system that can be controlled by increasingly cheap shelters.
Ultimately, Lebanon will find itself in a situation similar to that of Venezuela.
By contrast, the establishment of the new republic pushed by the revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
The revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon rather than abandon it.
They believe its performance falls far short of its potential, and performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, nepotism, and inequality.
They hope to establish a vibrant high-tech industry, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural powerhouse, and create more synergies with the diaspora communities.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank capital, and to forcibly reduce deposits of savers holding more than 1% of total deposits.
They support a moderate depreciation of the currency and a thorough improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corrupt practices and increased spending on social programs and infrastructure.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
The current infighting over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of a larger struggle in the country's pursuit of new political solutions.
The financial crisis poses a fatal threat to this country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
The future of Lebanon remains unresolved.
